    <url>/2020/10/16/Abstruct-algebra/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<h1 id="Quotient"><a href="#Quotient" class="headerlink" title="Quotient"></a>Quotient</h1><blockquote>
<p>Too much to learn</p>
</blockquote>
<h2 id="Quotient-Define-amp-Examples"><a href="#Quotient-Define-amp-Examples" class="headerlink" title="Quotient Define &amp; Examples"></a>Quotient Define &amp; Examples</h2><p>In the algebra, many system has its quotient system, like <code>quotient group</code>,<code>quotient set</code>, and so on.</p>
<h3 id="Quotient-Group"><a href="#Quotient-Group" class="headerlink" title="Quotient Group"></a>Quotient Group</h3><p>The quotient needs to define a relation just like $R$, to simplify the argument, I use group to discuss.</p>
<p>with the defined relationship, we have a <code>Left Coset</code> , the Left Cosets build up the <code>quotient group</code>, we can present each elements by the Representative of equivalence class, we write them as  $\bar a, \bar b \dots$ </p>
<p>$\bar a$ Represent each elements that equal to $a$ under the relationship ${R}$</p>
<p>the simplest example is the set $\mathbb{Z}$ under the calculate <code>+</code>, and $\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z}$, the quotient group of it.</p>
<p>the elements in $\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z} $, just like $\bar 1, \bar 2, \cdots, \overline{m-1}$, in the <code>+</code>, the equation is presented as $ \text{if } a - b = i$, so $a \&amp; b $ is in the set $\overline{i}$, in the $\times$ is the $ab^{-1} \in \overline{i}$.</p>
]]></content>
